<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
In metal_linux_dev_open, ldev is allocated unconditionally before entering the for_each_linux_driver loop (ldev = malloc(...); if (!ldev) return -ENOMEM;). Nothing in the shown code sets ldev to NULL before the inner fragment, so inside the loop the condition if (!ldev) and its consequent malloc (and the subsequent if (!ldev) return -ENOMEM;) will never lead to allocation or return. Removing those two checks and the allocation would not change program behaviour. Therefore those operations are dead code and violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2. (This conclusion assumes driver callbacks do not deliberately reset ldev to NULL; given the provided code, the checks are redundant.)
</scenario>
